    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Curtis E. Rodgers was born in Little Rock, Arkansas in 1935. He graduated from the University of Michigan with a BA in political science and did post-graduate work in business administration and law at Wayne State and the University of Detroit, respectively. In 1962 he began working for the city of Detroit in the community relations and welfare divisions. From 1966 to 1968, Rodgers worked as chief supervising assistant of community services in the Commission on Community Relations. In 1968 he was named as an aide to Detroit Mayor Jerome P. Cavanaugh. A year later, Rodgers succeeded Richard Marks as the Commission's director. In January 1970, Rodgers left the CCR to join the Legal Aid and Defenders Association. Rodgers later lived in New York City.</p>
      <p>While working for the city of Detroit, Rodgers involved himself heavily in debates regarding civil rights and equality. Specific issues included improving blacks' access to adequate primary schooling, removing bias in housing laws, expanding city patronage to minority owned businesses, increasing minority employment rates, reforming the police force, and mitigating the racially fueled violence that plagued Detroit in the late 1960s.</p>
      <p>Curtis E. Rodgers died July 22, 2009.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The Curtis E. Rodgers collection is comprised of three series: Personal, Detroit Commission on Community Relations, and Visual Materials. and dates from 1966 to 1971 (with one item from 1953). The series includes minutes, reports, and other agenda materials. There are also speeches, press releases, studies and subject files pertaining to the Commission on Community Relations. Subjects include employment, housing, the police force, education, and building safety.</p>
    </scopecontent>
